It=E2=80=99s easy to dismiss incumbents getting into crypto as just another=
 sign that we=E2=80=99re in a bubble. We=E2=80=99ve seen this movie before.=
 Early web3 mirrors the early commercial internet.=C2=A0
In 1999, during the frenzy of the dot com bubble, practically every company=
 built a website, and any company that added =E2=80=9C.com=E2=80=9D to thei=
r name soared in value. One 2001 study [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJ=
xFkE1uwyAQhU8TdrWGHzt4waKbXsMCM3FQMFiAG_n2ndiLIvRg9DS84ZttwyWXw2y5NvaRqR0bm=
oTvGrE1LGyvWKbgDR-Elr0amTfKc91rFur0KIirDdG0siPbdhfDbFvI6ewAED17Gm3vA_dopeCi=
nx_KSYUoOdVu1AM9dOba3QdMMxr8xXLkhCyaZ2tbvcnvm_ihnVMMCWNwxZaje4eIRzfnlRyfA6l=
1lZRDx2nRjeLFFwctOgAFNK8RIKiWQHNopTreidn1cEehBq25A-4HP4IfEe-ec_mAm4J1EV3dXW=
12fn3iWDEpN5dLSAvZr6ddMZ4GfX-ic91TaMeEybqI_iLTLsAnq2nBhIXA-8k2wipBElkJIPlFg=
tApUEMvlGSU7DN1pf_QP4BijYY] in The Journal of Finance found that companies =
that added =E2=80=9C.com,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C.net,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CInte=
rnet=E2=80=9D to their name saw their stock prices increase 74% in the days=
 following the name change.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s fun to look back and make fun of all of the silliness 1999/200=
0 silliness. Pets.com! Lol. Webvan haha! Internet.com teehee!=C2=A0
In the beginning, these shifts feel like bubbles. Internet mania drove the =
tech-heavy NASDAQ up 3.4x from 1,619 at the beginning of 1998 to a peak of =
4,696 in February 2000. It crashed even harder, to a low of 1,172 in Septem=
ber 2002. Oof.=C2=A0
But after an early peak and valley, the internet obviously stuck around. Th=
e dot com bubble looks like a big blip. Today, the NASDAQ sits at 15,129, 3=
=2E2x higher than it=E2=80=99s dot com p=
eak. Internet companies have created =
trillions of dollars in value. The technology is so ubiquitous that we no l=
onger talk about =E2=80=9Cdot com=E2=80=9D companies or =E2=80=9Cinternet=
=E2=80=9D companies. The most valuable companies were born of, or pivoted h=
ard towards, the internet. Early hype helped fund that shift.
NFTs today feel similar.=C2=A0
If I had an ETH for every time I=E2=80=99ve seen someone compare NFTs to Tu=
lip Mania [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OgzAMhU_TLJHzB3SRxWzmBLO=
PnMTQqJCgEKbi9pOWxUiWLfvJenqfx0pzLqfZ8l7Zu9l6bmQSvfaFaqXCjp2KjcHwXoxSqzsLRg=
U-6pHF3U6FaMW4mFoOYtvhluixxpw-HwBCs4dRg0OUkxc9TI40IZ9kPwnJOZIYYLp88QiRkidDv=
1TOnIgt5lHrtt_k1018t6LUveIzbhQidrnM7fTe2_g5lrjZFVNEFo0AwWGUwIUelep4J7zTMJBQ=
_ThyBzz04Q7hTjQEzuUENwXrLLr9cHtF_-x8XlkxKVeXS0xzk58PXGn5CC2kbXM9UqynpYRuoXD=
lrxfGDxE7U6LS8AaLtcGTIBs_CSD5lbcBUqB6LZRkzTnk9pX-Tf8A7tCJZg], I=E2=80=99d b=
e able to buy up all the CryptoPunks. But I think there=E2=80=99s a key dif=
ference: manias like the one that gripped the Dutch in the 17th Century or =
Beanie Baby collectors in the 1990s were isolated and non-composable. Money=
 thrown at Tulips or Beanie Babies didn=E2=80=99t spur innovation that othe=
rs could build on. There was no directional arrow. They were time capsules,=
 captured to be revisited and analyzed by future anthropologists.=C2=A0
If they are a bubble, NFTs are more like the dot com bubble. They=E2=80=99r=
e a different, more productive sort than Tulips. (Alright alright, except f=
or this $3.2M Tulip NFT [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMuOwyAMRb8mL=
CvzymPBYqRRl7OafUTATVETiIC0yt-P2yxGQoBl2efqOFtxTvkwWyqVva-xHhuaiK-yYK2Y2V4w=
j8Eb3opeajUwb5Tnve5ZKOMtI642LKbmHdm2T0twtoYUPxMAQrO7UTB0qtO-AyfE0Do-WQG9bjU=
KN93AnVy7-4DRocEn5iNFZIu517qVRn414kqnvsI70cWllarfPUfMP-lpH1SVaute6MOVFFwSuJ=
W81VqLTjfySku-BbBgBAgOvQQudK_UhV8ogoYOhWr7nk_AfesH8ANi5zmXN2gUrLO4lH0ihHu84=
SybmOqUcogztR93u-LyaZCAkd51j6EeI0Y7LehPN_VU_LE1zkjRSb0fbSWxEiS5lQCSny5IngLV=
aqEkI7JPNBX_oX-VhY5Q]). Unlike Tulips, bubbly demand for internet stocks or=
 NFTs brings more money and experimentation, which increases the likelihood=
 of building valuable use cases that gain mainstream adoption. Is there som=
e dumb shit being bid up to incomprehensible prices? Certainly. But in thes=
e cases, enthusiasm becomes activation energy, and over time, foolish behav=
ior fades and a new paradigm emerges. The internet and NFTs follow the old =
Not Boring favorite: the Gartner Hype Cycle [https://email.mg2.substack.com=
/c/eJxFkMuOwyAMRb-m7BqZR1KyYDGb-Y2Ih5ugEoiATJS_H9qMNBIyxvbVxcfqinPKp9pSqeQd=
pnpuqCIeJWCtmMleME_eKTowyXsxEqeEo7KXxJfpmRFX7YOqeUey7SZ4q6tP8aMAYD1ZFKOWUQ2=
2R2Fg0D0Yi-NjRABOnTSPy1fvzmO0qPAH85kikqCWWrdy41839t3OcRzdrHONmDub1lbB2ELGgj=
rbpaUr1iW5FNLssbT33_R9aTvd7WkDEq8YMAqSA2W9FKKjHbOmhwcyMUhJDVA3uBHciPhwlPIn3=
ASsM-vKbkrV9vX2JlnFVE3KPs6t_Vr0iuHTaAymdq979PWcMGoT0F146kX5A2yasX2s0XeTro0t=
B97w8jeSC0fjJ0AMPROcNGeXmir-m_4CpuWUUQ].=C2=A0
The Gartner Hype Cycle is a useful framework through which to view new tech=
nologies, particularly powerful for the fact that nearly every new major te=
chnological innovation follows its curve. It=E2=80=99s not that all technol=
ogies are the same, or become useful at the same rate; instead, the Hype Cy=
cle is a mirror that reflects humanity=E2=80=99s collective attitude toward=
s new things.=C2=A0
Some new technology gets built
We get really excited and imagine the myriad ways it might be used=C2=A0
Then we get disappointed when it doesn=E2=80=99t immediately fulfill all of=
 them
Then, over time, the truly valuable technologies find mainstream adoption a=
s they become part of the fabric of the way we do things.
According to Gartner itself:
Gartner Hype Cycles provide a graphic representation of the maturity and ad=
option of technologies and applications, and how they are potentially relev=
ant to solving real business problems and exploiting new opportunities. Gar=
tner Hype Cycle methodology gives you a view of how a technology or applica=
tion will evolve over time, providing a sound source of insight to manage i=
ts deployment within the context of your specific business goals.
Ultimately, it helps companies think about when to implement a new technolo=
gy.
Each year, Gartner places emerging technologies on the Hype Cycle. Last wee=
k, it released the 2021 Hype Cycle [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUU=
uu4yAQPE3Y2eLrkAWLt3nXsDC0bRQbImiP5dtPJxlpJASi-lPdVcEjLKVe7lUasvc14vUCl-FsG=
yBCZUeDOqboxCCtMvrBotNRWGNZauNcAXafNof1APY6pi0Fj6nkTwXn0rDVhUk8poHbMBkZtLfS=
8GGww6y9uXtl5i-vP2KCHMDBH6hXycA2tyK-2k393OQvnfM8-8VXzFD7UHZC2k5fqGfC9V-AQNX=
hCju0rh119gG6lN9IJ7kU3UrbdeEKG3RzqR3l1SXlpUMIay5bWRI06sGSe6dzq7iQxmrdi17S_P=
wOUg_WiomLOMQHjw-AexRCzfym-b7Ivh1TQx-e7xFZdbngVCpRUPi5-h22T4CkGundj5zwGiH7a=
YP4VRG_Znx0HRegpcikOHokCxRX5ILiXImvaiSz5nowUitGzLFQVf5P-hdndKJD]. Right at =
the top of the Peak of Inflated Expectations, of course, are NFTs.=C2=A0
Gartner=E2=80=99s customers are companies, not crypto degens. If Gartner is=
 including NFTs on the Hype Cycle, it means that companies are thinking abo=
ut how to incorporate them. Gartner seems to think that we=E2=80=99re at th=
e Peak of Inflated Expectations for NFTs, the point in the cycle at which, =
=E2=80=9CEarly publicity produces a number of success stories =E2=80=94 oft=
en accompanied by scores of failures. Some companies take action; many do n=
ot.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
NFTs=E2=80=99 placement at the top of the Peak likely contains a little bit=
 of truth and a whole lot of desire to grab headlines. There=E2=80=99s prob=
ably an interesting thing that happens when the Gartner team chooses where =
to place things. They might say, =E2=80=9CWhich technology could we place a=
t the Peak of Inflated Expectations to drive the most clicks?=E2=80=9D and =
whatever the answer is is probably also the technology that really is at th=
e Peak of Inflated Expectations.=C2=A0
Anyway, we=E2=80=99re still early. At this point in the cycle, some compani=
es experiment with the technology, many don=E2=80=99t. A handful of the one=
s who do are going to drop some embarrassingly harebrained NFTs or acquire =
NFTs for too much money. We may have the opportunity to look back in a year=
, from the Trough of Disillusionment, and laugh at the most ill-conceived. =
But that doesn=E2=80=99t mean we should dismiss NFTs. Au contraire. Technol=
ogies that Gartner places at the Peak often go on to create orders of magni=
tude more value than they=E2=80=99re worth at the time of Peak placement.=
=C2=A0
See, I love the Hype Cycle, but it=E2=80=99s also a bit misleading. With ju=
st a glance at the graph, it would seem as if technologies never live up to=
 their initial hype, like investing at the peak would inevitably lead to lo=
sses. Even the companies that survive the Trough of Disillusionment can onl=
y hope to end up at the dull-sounding =E2=80=9CPlateau of Productivity.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0
But the Y-axis represents =E2=80=9Cexpectations,=E2=80=9D not value, and ju=
st looking at the chart dramatically undersells the value that mass-adopted=
 technologies create. Take Web 2.0, for example.=C2=A0
